Deterministic Finite Automaton (DFA):
A DFA has a single unique computation path for each input string.
1. Formal Definition: A DFA is a 5-tuple (Q, Σ, 8, 90, F):
Q: A finite set of states.
•
Σ: The alphabet (finite set of input symbols).
•
¿ : Q × Σ → Q: The transition function, which maps a state and an input symbol to a
single next state.
qo: The initial state (‰ EQ).
F: A set of accepting states (F C Q).
2. Key Characteristics:
•
.
For each state and input symbol, there is exactly one transition to a next state.
At any given time, the DFA is in a single state.
The DFA always "knows" where to go, as the next state is uniquely determined.

Nondeterministic Finite Automaton (NFA):
An NFA allows multiple computation paths for the same input string, including the use of epsilon (
€) transitions (transitions without consuming input).
1. Formal Definition: An NFA is a 5-tuple (Q, Σ, 8, 90, F):
Q: A finite set of states.
•
Σ: The alphabet (finite set of input symbols).
•
¿ : Q × (Σ U {e}) → 2º: The transition function, which maps a state and an input
symbol (or €) to a set of possible next states.
qo: The initial state (ɖo Є Q).
F: A set of accepting states (F ≤ Q).
2. Key Characteristics:
•
•
•
For each state and input symbol, there may be multiple possible next states (or none at
all).
The NFA can "guess" which path to take, effectively exploring multiple paths
simultaneously.
Epsilon (e) transitions allow the automaton to change states without consuming any
input.
